{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505434"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:30:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:30:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2442"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2442"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.1,0.06,0.65,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2442"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78764"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2442"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2442"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64113"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3736"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1944"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1956"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27050"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44272"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78764"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of severe pruritus that worsens after hot showers. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His vital signs are within normal limits. His face appears flushed with cyanotic lips. His jugular venous pressure is normal. His spleen is palpable 4 cm below the costal margin. Chest examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory results reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin = 209 g/L (135-180)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count = 9.1 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets = 320 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Corticosteroids","Hydroxycarbamide","Interferon alfa","Serial phlebotomy","Splenectomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of polycythaemia vera (PV), including aquagenic pruritus, facial plethora, cyanotic lips, splenomegaly and elevated haemoglobin. Given his age and absence of previous thrombosis, he is considered low-risk for thrombotic complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerial phlebotomy\u003C/strong\u003E combined with low-dose aspirin is the first-line treatment for low-risk PV patients. This approach effectively reduces blood viscosity by lowering the haematocrit while providing thromboprophylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECytoreduction is reserved for high-risk patients (age \u0026gt;60 years or previous thrombosis). This patient meets neither criterion. \u003Cstrong\u003EHydroxycarbamide\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0is commonly used for this indication. However,\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Einterferon alfa\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0is an alternative when hydroxycarbamide is contraindicated (e.g., during pregnancy).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E have no role in PV management. They are used in autoimmune conditions such as immune thrombocytopenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplenectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for PV as the underlying pathology is in the bone marrow. It may be considered in certain autoimmune haematological conditions but would not address the myeloproliferative process in PV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of PV can be confirmed with JAK2 mutation testing. Other causes of absolute polycythaemia (increased red cell mass) include secondary causes with elevated erythropoietin, while relative polycythaemia occurs with reduced plasma volume.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Serial phlebotomy with low-dose aspirin is first-line treatment for polycythaemia vera in patients with low thrombotic risk.","Aquagenic pruritus (itching after hot showers) is a characteristic symptom of polycythaemia vera.","Cytoreduction is indicated for polycythaemia vera patients with high thrombotic risk (age \u003E60 or previous thrombosis)."],"references":["Tefferi A, Barbui T. Polycythemia vera: 2024 update on diagnosis, risk-stratification, and management. American Journal of Hematology. 2023;98(9):1465\u201387."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64113"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2442"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64113"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T16:42:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T16:43:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2442"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78764"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"m